	"reelmower:guide-assembly-title": "Reel Mower: Some Assembly Required",
	"reelmower:guide-assembly-text": "<strong>Nothing here comes pre-built.</strong><br>Every piece of this mower gets made and put together by hand — including which wood it's made of. Here's the whole chain, start to finish.<br><br><strong>1. Smith the blade</strong><br>Forge a blade blank at the anvil from two ingots of the same metal, then finish it off in the crafting grid with a hammer and chisel.<br><br><strong>2. Build the frame</strong><br>Craft the frame in the grid from two metal plates, an ingot, and two rusty gears. Iron only — it has to be rigid enough to carry the blade.<br><br><strong>3. Carve the shaft</strong><br>Grab any log — all twelve wood types work — and turn it into a shaft with a chisel and a hammer. Whatever wood you pick is what you'll see on the finished mower, so choose for looks if you want to.<br><br><strong>4. Hammer it together</strong><br>Set the frame down on the ground. Hold a hammer in your main hand and equip the shaft in your offhand, then tap <hk>leftmouse</hk> (attack) on the frame three separate times — tap it, don't hold it down, so each swing plays out fully — no sneak needed, just walk up and swing, same as hitting an anvil. That's three nails total, one consumed per hit, so make sure you're carrying at least that many before you start. Third hit, and the frame becomes a bladeless mower right there on the spot.<br><br><strong>5. Seat the blade</strong><br>Hold the blade and <hk>shift</hk> + <hk>rightmouse</hk> click the bladeless mower. That's it — your mower, your wood, your metal.<br><br><strong>Want a different wood after the fact?</strong><br>If there's a blade in it, pop that off first with an empty hand (<hk>shift</hk> + <hk>rightmouse</hk> click). Then hold a chisel in your main hand, a hammer in your offhand, and <hk>rightmouse</hk> click the bare bladeless mower (sneak not required here either) — the shaft comes back to you in one piece, same wood it always was, ready to swap for something else. The nails don't come back perfectly though — pulled-out nails are a bit bent up, so each one has a chance of not being reusable. Whatever metal you used going in is what comes back out, copper stays copper, steel stays steel.",

	"reelmower:handbook-mowerframe-title": "What's this for?",
	"reelmower:handbook-mowerframe-text": "This is the skeleton, not the finished tool. Set it down on the ground, then hold a hammer in your main hand with a shaft (made from any log) in your offhand and hammer it on — three hits, three nails total. See the Reel Mower assembly guide for the full walkthrough.",

	"reelmower:handbook-mowershaft-title": "What's this for?",
	"reelmower:handbook-mowershaft-text": "The handle, carved from whatever log you had on hand. Hammer it onto a placed frame to start building a mower — the wood you used here is the wood you'll see on the finished thing. See the Reel Mower assembly guide for the full walkthrough.",

	"reelmower:handbook-reelmower-bladeless-title": "Almost there",
	"reelmower:handbook-reelmower-bladeless-text": "Frame and shaft, joined — just needs a blade. Hold a finished blade and right-click this (while it's on the ground) to seat it. Changed your mind on the wood? A chisel and a hammer will pull the shaft back off. See the Reel Mower assembly guide for the full walkthrough.",

	"reelmower:handbook-reelmower-title": "Built, not bought",
	"reelmower:handbook-reelmower-text": "Every piece of this — frame, shaft, blade — was assembled by hand, and the wood you see is whatever log you picked for the shaft. Three cut modes on the tool wheel: Trim, Remove, and Clear. Hang it on a Dowels peg (or a regular Tool Rack) when you're done for the day. See the Reel Mower assembly guide for the full walkthrough."
}
